message.content: We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. Phenylalanine hydroxylase is an enzyme needed to break down phenylalanine, and its deficiency can lead to phenylketonuria (PKU). PKU patients require a low phenylalanine diet and supplementation of tyrosine, which is normally produced from phenylalanine.

We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. Phenylalanine hydroxylase deficiency leads to an inability to break down phenylalanine to tyrosine, so dietary supplementation of tyrosine is necessary. Leucine, Aspartame, and Niacin are not directly related to this deficiency.

We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. Phenylalanine hydroxylase enzyme is responsible for converting phenylalanine to tyrosine. A deficit of this enzyme leads to a buildup of phenylalanine, which can be harmful to the developing brain. Therefore, dietary supplementation of tyrosine is required to provide an alternative source of this amino acid and prevent its deficiency. None of the other options are related to this condition.

Therefore, the child will require dietary supplementation of tyrosine. Leucine is an essential amino acid, aspartame is an artificial sweetener, and niacin is a B vitamin.

Therefore, a deficit of this enzyme will result in a buildup of phenylalanine and a decreased level of tyrosine. The child will require dietary supplementation of tyrosine to compensate for the deficit of this essential amino acid.
